        "  - Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with respect to the project: Age is not accurately represented because the dataset only lists the birthday. Therefore, we will need to calculate age another way.\n",
        "- **Dataset #4**\n",
        "  - Dataset Name: Bloomington, Indiana Intakes and Outcomes \n",
        "  - Link to the dataset: https://data.bloomington.in.gov/Public-Works/Animal-Shelter-Animals/e245-r9ub/about_data \n",
        "  - Number of observations: 42865\n",
        "  - Number of variables: 23\n",
        "  - Description of the variables most relevant to this project: The variables most relevant to this project include speciesname, breedname, basecolor, animalage, sexname, intakedate, movementdate, and movementtype. Speciesname allows us to restrict the analysis to dogs in order to maintain consistency across observations. Breedname and basecolor capture physical characteristics that may influence adoption likelihood or length of stay, as certain breeds and appearances are often preferred by adopters. Animalage is a key demographic variable, as age is strongly associated with adoption outcomes and shelter duration. sexname allows us to examine whether male and female dogs experience different outcome patterns. Intakedate and movementdate enable the calculation of length of stay, which is central to understanding how long animals remain in the shelter before exiting. Finally, movementype serves as the primary outcome variable, indicating whether the animal was adopted, transferred, euthanized, or otherwise exited the shelter. Together, these variables provide both predictor variables and a clearly defined outcome measure for modeling adoption dynamics and shelter movement patterns.\n",
        "  - Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with respect to the project: One limitation of this dataset is inconsistency in the recording of breed information. Many dogs are labeled broadly as “mix” without specification of the contributing breeds, while others are recorded with detailed breed combinations. This inconsistency may reduce the precision of breed-based analyses and introduce noise into categorical modeling. Additionally, breed labeling in shelter environments is often based on visual assessment rather than genetic testing, which may lead to misclassification. Although the dataset is largely complete with minimal missing entries, these inconsistencies in breed detail may limit the strength of conclusions drawn regarding breed-specific adoption trends. Additionally, shelter data generally lacks behavioral assessments, medical history, or prior ownership information, which could also influence movement outcomes but are not captured in this dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Combining Datasets #1 and #3:**\n",
