        "### Dataset #1: Austin, Texas Animal Shelter Dogs Intakes and Outtakes\n",
        "\n",
        "**A. Describe the important metrics, what units they are in, and give some sense of what they mean.**\n",
        "\n",
        "We are only looking at the shelter date for dogs therefore the animal type column would be useful to differentiate dogs from cats. The metrics we would be looking at would include age upon intake, time in shelter, and outcome type since we hypothesize that younger dogs and dogs without medical conditions will have a higher probability of adoption. The age upon intake data are floats (ex. 10.0), the time in the shelter column uses days (ex. 5 days), and the outcome type column uses one of the following: adoption, euthanasia, return to owner, and transfer. We are also considering the breed of dogs because we want to analyze our results to see if there is any difference in adoption rates between dog breeds.  \n",
        "\n",
        "**B. If there are any major concerns with the dataset, describe them.**\n",
        "\n",
        "We are concerned that the classification of dogs’ ages may be inaccurate for stray dogs. When dogs are taken into the shelter their age is estimated at the shelter. Health components are used to determine the age of a dog, for example their teeth are indicators of age in terms of dental wear and tartar. However the state of stray animals teeth may be in worse condition, resulting in stray dogs seeming to be of older age. \n",
        "\n",
        "Many dogs in the shelter are some type of a mix, and it would be illogical for shelters to test for full breed animals. Therefore when analyzing our data to see if our hypothesis holds when comparing dogs of similar breeds there would be some type of bias and we may not want to compare breeds if they are not fully accurate. \n",
        "The health status of dogs could also be inaccurate since a dog could have health issues that aren't visible or obvious. It is also unlikely for regular updates on animal health to be done accurately or even at all. There are also different classification or an animal being ill so this metric becomes inconsistent. Therefore this column better represents visible, obvious, and even serious health issues since there is no evidence to show the true health status of dogs. \n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import os\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "# Dataset: Austin (raw load)\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "austin_raw = pd.read_csv(\"data/00-raw/austin-texas-intakes-outcomes.csv\")\n",
        "austin = austin_raw.copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "pd.set_option(\"display.max_columns\", None)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Austin (raw) shape:\", austin.shape)\n",
        "austin.info()\n",
        "\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "# Missingness overview\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "missing_pct = (austin.isna().mean() * 100).sort_values(ascending=False)\n",
        "display(missing_pct.head(15))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Missingness pattern for outcome_subtype (often conditional on outcome_type)\n",
        "missing_subtype = pd.crosstab(\n",
        "    austin[\"outcome_type\"],\n",
        "    austin[\"outcome_subtype\"].isna(),\n",
        "    normalize=\"index\"\n",
        ")\n",
        "display(missing_subtype)\n",
        "\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "# Cleaning / Wrangling\n",
        "# -------------------------\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fill outcome_subtype NA as \"Not Applicable\" (structural missingness)\n",
        "austin[\"outcome_subtype\"] = austin[\"outcome_subtype\"].fillna(\"Not Applicable\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert datetimes safely\n",
        "austin[\"date_of_birth\"] = pd.to_datetime(austin[\"date_of_birth\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "austin[\"intake_datetime\"] = pd.to_datetime(austin[\"intake_datetime\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "austin[\"outcome_datetime\"] = pd.to_datetime(austin[\"outcome_datetime\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Drop rows missing the core outcome label (central to analysis; very small count)\n",
        "austin = austin.dropna(subset=[\"outcome_type\"]).copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fill small sex missingness\n",
        "austin[\"sex_upon_outcome\"] = austin[\"sex_upon_outcome\"].fillna(\"Unknown\")\n",
        "austin[\"sex_upon_intake\"] = austin[\"sex_upon_intake\"].fillna(\"Unknown\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Compute length of stay in days\n",
        "# Austin has time_in_shelter_days already, but we also compute LOS from datetimes as a cross-check.\n",
        "austin[\"length_of_stay_days\"] = (\n",
        "    (austin[\"outcome_datetime\"] - austin[\"intake_datetime\"]).dt.total_seconds() / (60 * 60 * 24)\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Remove impossible LOS values (negative or missing due to bad timestamps)\n",
        "austin = austin[\n",
        "    austin[\"length_of_stay_days\"].notna() &\n",
        "    (austin[\"length_of_stay_days\"] >= 0)\n",
        "].copy()\n",
        "\n",
